improveFood.title: Your Personalised Food Recommendations
improveFood.content:
Eat your way to good health! Below are some food ingredients we recommend you eat more of to improve your gut diversity and overall health.
Click the button below for our full list of recommendations.

IMMUNITY.title: Immunity Formulation
IMMUNITY.content: Congratulations! You have good scores across all your wellness categories. The Immunity Formulation helps you maintain your health while boosting your immunity. This formulation contains the B. animalis ssp. lactis strain that primes the body's immune system (through a process called immunomodulation) to fight infection.

WELL_BEING.title: Well-being Formulation
WELL_BEING.content: You report indicates poor scores across all your wellness categories. However, this is no time to worry. The Well-being Formulation is designed to improve your overall physical and mental well-being. It contains L.plantarum and B.longum which protect your heart health by reducing TMAO, increase beneficial bile acid metabolism, and increase the production of neurotransmitters which positively affect mood, sleep, and stress management.

ENERGY.title: Energy Formulation
ENERGY.content: Your report indicates poor Feel Well scores. However, this is no time to worry. The Energy Formulation is designed to boost your energy levels and contains L.paracasei and L.rhamnosus which increase the production of short chain fatty acids and help to efficiently metabolise food.

MIND.title: Mind Formulation
MIND.content: Your report indicates poor Think Well scores. However, this is no time to worry.The Mind formulation is designed to improve your mental well-being and contains B.breve which has been shown to reduce stress, improve mood and memory.

STRENGTH.title: Strength Formulation
STRENGTH.content: Your report indicates poor Live Well scores. However, this is no time to worry. The Strength Formulation is designed to boost your physical well-being and contains the L.reuteri strain which helps to maintain gut health and reduce fatigue.

supplements.title: Supplements
supplements.content: From the Greek 'Pro-bios' meaning 'good for life', these are specific strains of live, good bacteria that have proven health benefits. These bacteria aim to add a little zest to your microbiome and boost the species currently present in your gut. Additionally, you can boost these with probiotic supplements much like vitamins. Supercharge your microbiome with some good bacteria, hand-picked just for you!

connectWithHealtCoach.title: Connect with a Health Coach
connectWithHealtCoach.content:
Still have questions? Got a health goal in mind?
Connect with our health coaches to further deep dive into your gut microbiome and get further recommendations on how to control your health.

thinkWell.title: Think Well
thinkWell.desc:
Have you ever had butterflies in your tummy because you were nervous about something? That was your brain talking to your gut! Your gut and brain are very closely connected, both physically and biochemically. They ‘communicate’ through a complex network known as the ‘gut-brain axis’.

Neurotransmitters are the brain’s messengers. They form an important part of the gut-brain axis. They are chemicals produced in your body that influence your feelings and mood – like the brain's postmen, delivering information between different sites of the brain. These are largely produced in the body, but interestingly, the gut microbiome has been shown to produce neurotransmitters too!

In particular, the bacteria in your gut produce GABA (gamma-aminobutyric acid) and serotonin, both of which have significant impact on how we feel emotionally.

Read on to find out more and discover how your gut microbiome may be influencing your brain!
thinkWell.Great: The Think Well score measures the overall state of your neurotransmission pathways – GABA and Serotonin, both of which have significant impact on how we feel emotionally. Your score is great, which means that your gut microbiome is positively influencing your feelings and mood. Great job!
thinkWell.Good: The Think Well score measures the overall state of your neurotransmission pathways – GABA and Serotonin, both of which have significant impact on how we feel emotionally. Your score is good, which means that your gut microbiome is positively influencing your feelings and mood. Good job!
thinkWell.Poor: The Think Well score measures the overall state of your neurotransmission pathways – GABA and Serotonin, both of which have significant impact on how we feel emotionally. Your score tells us that you are in the poor range, which means that your gut microbiome is not living up to its fullest potential in influencing your feelings and mood. This can be improved!

liveWell.title: Live Well
liveWell.desc:
Your gut microbiome is closely tied to many aspects of your overall health. Apart from regulating digestion, the bacteria in your gut produce chemicals that can contribute to other health conditions.

We’ve identified three main categories of conditions that can be influenced by your microbiome:

1. Heart Health: Bacterial activity that is associated with heart disease or even stroke

2. Gut Health: Contributory factors to the proper functioning of your gut lining that can be affected in conditions like IBS or malabsorption

3. Liver Health: The ‘loop-like’ relationship your gut microbiome has with bile acid

Apart from these three categories, we have also identified a number of key areas that relate to your overall health.
liveWell.Great: The Live Well score measures the overall state of your heart, gut, and liver health. Your score is great, which means that your gut microbiome is positively influencing your heart, gut, and liver health. Great job!
liveWell.Good: The Live Well score measures the overall state of your heart, gut, and liver health. Your score is good, which means that your gut microbiome is positively influencing your heart, gut, and liver health. Good job!
liveWell.Poor: The Live Well score measures the overall state of your heart, gut, and liver health. Your score tells us that you are in the poor range, which means that your gut microbiome is not living up to its fullest potential in influencing your heart, gut, and liver health. This can be improved!

feelWell.title: Feel Well
feelWell.desc:
Your gut microbiome is largely responsible for digesting the food you consume. In doing so, it generates energy that fuels your cells and, by extension, you! It’s important to understand how efficient your microbes are at digesting food to generate energy, as well as whether they produce the right chemicals to allow you to make full use of this energy.This section of your report has been broken into two parts:

1. Food metabolism

2. Energy harvest

The first section will explain how efficient your gut microbiome is at digesting carbohydrates, proteins, and fats to produce energy.

The second section will explore your production of short-chain fatty acids (SCFAs), important compounds that help us produce, store, and use energy.
feelWell.Great: The Feel Well score measures the overall state of your gut’s energy harvesting pathways as well as your metabolic activity. Your score tells us that you are in the great score range, which means that your gut microbiome is efficiently metabolising food and harvesting energy. Great job!
feelWell.Good: The Feel Well score measures the overall state of your gut’s energy harvesting pathways as well as your metabolic activity. Your score tells us that you are in the average score range, which means that your gut is efficiently metabolising food and harvesting energy. Good job!
feelWell.Poor: The Feel Well score measures the overall state of your gut’s energy harvesting pathways as well as your metabolic activity. Your score tells us that you are in the poor score range, which means that your gut microbiome may be inefficiently metabolising food and harvesting energy. This can be improved!

vitaminB.title: Vitamin B
vitaminB.desc:
B vitamins play a vital role in maintaining good health and well-being. As the building blocks of a healthy body they have a direct impact on your energy levels, brain function, and cell metabolism.

Many of the B vitamins are synthesised or co-produced by the gut microbiome. In this section, we have measured how well your gut does in the synthesis of these specific B vitamins.

foodMetabolism.title: Food Metabolism
foodMetabolism.desc: The gut microbiome is largely responsible for digestion. Different bacterial groups are responsible for breaking down a variety of food components such as carbohydrates, proteins, and fats.

energyHarvest.title: Energy Harvest
energyHarvest.desc:
Your gut microbiome impacts your energy balance. A well-balanced gut microbiome can increase your ability to harvest and absorb energy from your food intake and produce substances like short-chain fatty acids (SCFAs). SCFAs impact your body’s ability to produce, store, and use energy.

One of the most important functions of SCFAs is providing energy for the cells that line your colon. Different SCFAs serve other roles such as maintaining the PH balance in your gut, protecting your body against inflammation, and regulating your fat use and storage.

gutHealth.title: Gut Health
gutHealth.desc: Cysteine and indole are known to protect the intestinal lining - the cells that form the gate between digested food and blood vessels that absorb nutrition. They help keep the integrity of the cells and assist in reducing inflammation of the gut.

oxidativeStress.title: Oxidative Stress
oxidativeStress.desc: Oxidative stress is described as the imbalance between the availability of reactive oxygen species (ROS) and the body’s ability to detoxify these ROS. While a baseline level of ROS is required for cellular functioning, an imbalance or detoxification lag can cause tissue damage. In the long run, oxidative stress has been linked with cancer, neurodegenerative disorders, and a host of other diseases
oxidativeStress.Great:
Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups involved in producing reactive oxygen species (ROS) was found to be in the optimum range.

This means that your gut microbiome is not producing a significant amount of ROS, and oxidative stress is low. This is great!
oxidativeStress.Good:
Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups involved in producing reactive oxygen species (ROS) are slightly low.

This is no cause for concern as it means your gut microbiome is not producing a significant amount of ROS, and oxidative stress is low. This is good!
oxidativeStress.Poor:
Your results indicate that the bacterial groups involved in producing reactive oxygen species (ROS) are high.

This means that your gut microbiome is producing a significant amount of ROS, and oxidative stress is high. This potentially links to many diseases such as neurodegenerative disorders and even inflammation. This can be improved!

GABA.title: GABA
GABA.desc:
GABA is an important neurotransmitter. An abundance of GABA is known to have a calming effect, helping with feelings of anxiety and stress.

We measure your GABA score by looking for bacteria in your gut that are known to produce GABA. The more GABA-producing bacteria you have, the more GABA you are likely to produce.
GABA.Great: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with GABA production was found to be high. This means that your gut microbiome can produce sufficient GABA naturally, helping to keep you calm and relaxed. This is great!
GABA.Good: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with your GABA levels was found to be average. This means that your gut microbiome can produce sufficient GABA naturally, helping to keep you calm and relaxed. This is good!
GABA.Poor: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with your GABA levels was found to be low. This means that your gut microbiome may be producing less GABA naturally, and you could be stressed or anxious as a result. This can be improved!

Serotonin.title: Serotonin
Serotonin.desc: Serotonin is a great multitasker – it has a widespread effect on many aspects of your body, ranging from your emotional behaviour to your motor skills. It regulates feelings of happiness, helps to control bowel movements, influences your sleep cycles, and even contributes to bone health!
Serotonin.Great: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with serotonin production was found to be high. This means you have plenty of serotonin to spare, keeping you and your body happy. This is great!
Serotonin.Good: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with serotonin production was found to be average. This means you are producing a sufficient amount of serotonin to keep you and your body happy. This is good!
Serotonin.Poor: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with serotonin production was found to be low. This means that your gut microbiome may not be producing sufficient serotonin naturally, and may  affect your feelings and mood. This can be improved!

Butyrate.title: Butyrate
Butyrate.desc: Butyrate impacts your body's satiety level (level of feeling full), your gut lining, and even your sensitivity to insulin.
Butyrate.Great: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with butyrate production was found to be high. This means you are producing enough butyrate to keep your satiety levels normal and maintain your gut lining. This is great!
Butyrate.Good: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with butyrate production was found to be above average. This means you are producing enough butyrate to keep your satiety levels normal and maintain your gut lining. This is good!
Butyrate.Poor: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with your butyrate production was found to be low. This means you may not be producing enough butyrate to keep your satiety levels normal and maintain your gut lining. This can be improved!

Lactate.title: Lactate
Lactate.desc: Lactate tolerance measures your body's response to strain. Generally, individuals with high exercise tolerances have higher abundances of lactate metabolising bacteria.
Lactate.Great: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with lactate metabolism was found to be high. As a result, you might be very tolerant to exercise. This is great!
Lactate.Good: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with lactate metabolism was found to be average. As a result, you might be relatively tolerant to exercise. This is good!
Lactate.Poor: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with lactate metabolism was found to be low. As a result, you might be less tolerant to exercise. This can be improved!

BranchedChainAminoAcids.title: Branched Chain Amino Acids
BranchedChainAminoAcids.desc: Branched-chain amino acids (BCAAs) stimulate the building of protein in muscle and possibly reduce muscle breakdown. BCAAs in certain quantities also regulate glucose levels in blood. The levels of BCAAs in the body is mediated largely by the gut microbiome.
BranchedChainAminoAcids.Great: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with BCAA availability was found to be high. This means that your gut microbiome may be producing a large amount of BCAAs, helping you to build and repair muscles faster, along with regulating glucose levels in blood. This is great!
BranchedChainAminoAcids.Good: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with BCAA availability was found to be above average. This means that your gut microbiome may be producing a sufficient amount of BCAAs, helping you to build and repair muscles faster, along with regulating glucose levels in blood. This is good!
BranchedChainAminoAcids.Poor: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with BCAA availability was found to be low. This means that your gut microbiome may not be producing enough BCAAs. This may result in inefficient muscle building, repair, and glucose level regulation. This can be improved!

VitaminB1.desc: Vitamin B1 (Thiamine) plays an essential role in metabolism by helping convert nutrients into energy.
VitaminB1.Great: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with Vitamin B1 production was found to be high, potentially improving your metabolism. This is great!
VitaminB1.Good: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with Vitamin B1 production was found to be average, potentially maintaining your metabolism. This is good!

Tryptophan.desc: Tryptophan is an essential amino acid, which means it is not produced by the body but acquired through diet. Tryptophan has an important role in neurotransmitter production, and several other key metabolic activities. The importance of Tryptophan spans from neurological activity to metabolism and even gut wellness. It is a building block of major biomolecules in the body, most of which is carried out by the microbiome.
Tryptophan.Great: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with tryptophan metabolism was in the optimal range. This means that your gut microbiome is producing sufficient tryptophan naturally to make essential biomolecules, boosting your emotional wellness. This is great!
Tryptophan.Good: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with tryptophan metabolism was higher than the average. This is no cause for concern as your gut microbiome is producing sufficient tryptophan naturally to make essential biomolecules, maintaining your emotional wellness. This is good!

While a baseline level of ROS is required for cellular functioning, an imbalance or detoxification lag can cause tissue damage. In the long run, oxidative stress has been linked with cancer, neurodegenerative disorders, and a host of other diseases.

ImidazolePropionate.Great: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with your Imidazole Propionate production processes was found to be in the optimum range.This means that your microbiome's production of imidazole propionate is in check, keeping your metabolic health in the right range. Great job!
ImidazolePropionate.Good: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with your Imidazole Propionate production processes was found to be lower than average. This means that your microbiome's production of imidazole propionate is in check, keeping your metabolic health in the right range. This is good!

This means that your gut microbiome may be producing a larger amount of Imidazole Propionate, which may be affecting your metabolic health. This can be improved!

BileAcidPool.title: Bile Acid Pool
BileAcidPool.desc:
One of the elements that keeps the gut microbiome in check is bile acid. The bile acid pool refers to the amount of bile acid in your body. Mainly produced in the liver, bile acid serves many functions in the body. Among these, it serves important functions such as fat digestion and regulation of the gut microbiome to prevent an overgrowth of bacteria. In turn, the gut bacteria contribute to the formation of bile acid pools.

A reduced bile acid pool may lead to bacterial overgrowth and inflammation in the gut microbiome, leading to digestive or bowel issues.
BileAcidPool.Great: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups responsible for contributing to the bile acid pool was found to be in the optimum range. This indicates that your bile acid pool size is large enough to keep your gut microbiome in check. This is great!
BileAcidPool.Good: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups responsible for contributing to the bile acid pool was found to be above average. This is no cause for concern as it means that your bile acid pool size is large enough to keep your gut microbiome in check. This is good!
BileAcidPool.Poor: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups responsible for contributing to the bile acid pool was found to be low. This indicates that your bile acid pool size might be reduced, this could contribute to overgrowth of bacteria. This can be improved!

IndoleDerivatives.title: Indole & Indole Derivatives
IndoleDerivatives.Great: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups responsible for indole production was in the optimal range. This means that you are producing plenty of indole to keep your gut lining healthy. This is great!
IndoleDerivatives.Good: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups responsible for indole production was found to be high. This is no cause for concern as it means that you are producing enough indole to maintain your gut lining. This is good!
IndoleDerivatives.Poor: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups responsible for indole production was found to be low. This means that your gut microbiome may not be producing enough indole on its own to maintain your gut lining. This can be improved!

CysteineAndDerivatives.title: Cysteine & Derivatives
CysteineAndDerivatives.Great: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups responsible for cysteine production was found to be high. This means that you are producing plenty of cysteine to keep your gut lining healthy. This is great!
CysteineAndDerivatives.Good: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups responsible for cysteine production was found to be average. This means that you are producing enough cysteine to maintain your gut lining. This is good!
CysteineAndDerivatives.Poor: Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups responsible for cysteine production was found to be low. This means that your gut microbiome may not be producing enough cysteine on its own to maintain your gut lining. This can be improved!

TMAO.title: TMAO
TMAO.desc: Trimethylamine N-oxides, also known as TMAO, is a biomolecule produced during digestion that has been strongly associated with an increased risk of heart disease, stroke, and other cardiovascular diseases. TMAO is formed in the liver from a building block known as Trimethylamine, or TMA. TMA is produced by certain strains of bacteria in your gut during digestion. The more of those bacteria you have, the greater the amount of TMA and TMAO you can expect to find in your body.
TMAO.Great: Trimethylamine N-oxide (TMAO): Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with  TMAO production processes was found to be low. This means that your gut microbiome is not producing a significant amount of TMAO or TMA. Great job!
TMAO.Good: Trimethylamine N-oxide (TMAO): Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with your TMAO production processes was found to be average. This means that your gut microbiome is producing an average amount of TMAO or TMA. This is good but can be improved further!
TMAO.Poor: Trimethylamine N-oxide (TMAO): Your results indicate that the concentration of bacterial groups associated with your TMAO production processes was found to be high. This means that your gut microbiome may be producing a larger amount of TMAO or TMA. In the long run, TMAO has been shown to be associated with heart disease. This can be improved!

inflammatory.desc: Inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) is an umbrella term used to describe disorders that involve chronic inflammation of the digestive tract. nash.title: NASH
nash.desc: Non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH) is liver inflammation and damage caused by a buildup of fat in the liver. It is part of a group of conditions called non-alcoholic fatty liver disease. Many people have a build-up of fat in the liver, and for most it causes no symptoms and no problems. In some people, fat causes inflammation and damages liver cells. NASH can cause scarring of the liver, leading to cirrhosis.
